            <h2>
                Project 2 - InstructAR
            </h2>
            <p>
                The InstructAR project had one main requirement: help children with autism better understand how to
                follow ordered steps. This project proved very challenging since there were so many approaches worth
                considering. Something that narrowed our scope was the accessibility of the students who would be using
                the app. To better understand the requirements of these children and their teachers, we prioritized
                research and held conversations with our supervisor who had a great deal more experience working with
                children with autism than our group did.
                <br><br> For this project I lead the design of the wireframes and below are iterations 1-3 of the
                design. In iteration 1, we started with a low-fidelity wireframe knowing we wanted the primary function
                to be the completion of steps and hoped to incorporate a lego build into it. In iteration 2, after
                further discussion of our main user persona (teacher), we added elements for them to select a specific
                challenge. Finally, in iteration 3, designs were added to the wireframes to make a prototype with as
                much of the user flow as we could think of. Due to covid disrupting plans, our design was molded even
                further into our final design.
                <br><br> Note: these wireframes were exported into Figma from Adobe XD causing them to lose their
                interactivity. To see the interactivity, check out the corresponding links below each embedded Figma
                file to jump to an Adobe XD live preview.

            </p>
