            <h2>
                Project 3 - Flash Cards
            </h2>
            <p>
                During the spring and summer of 2020, I had the opportunity to work on a project through the GIMM
                Development team in which our clients were a deaf literacy program from Georgia. Included below is the
                work I did for an interactive digital flashcard experience I made while on the project. I also had the
                opportunity to cover the project manager position while being a designer which allowed me to meet with
                clients, assess requirements, design wireframes, iterate designs based on their critiques, then program
                the design in Phaser; a JavaScript framework. <br><br>
                The primary challenge for this project was my personal lack of knowledge of deaf literacy. Prior to
                starting, I was unaware that there was a need for a different curriculum for students who had access to
                sound and those that didn’t as I had assumed only students without access to sound would partake in deaf
                literacy. Due to this lack of exposure, I unintentionally designed flashcards that did not accommodate
                all students. This created some confusion with the client until we were able to resolve our
                miscommunications through prototyping and listening to their critiques. This emphasized the importance
                for me of asking questions in the original requirements meeting and of creating early prototypes for the
                client to address any concerns prior to spending time inefficiently on production. <br><br>
                Below is some sketch work I made during a meeting with the client to bridge our understanding of what
                was wanted and what I understood was wanted.

